\begin_body

\begin_layout Chapter
Service-coverage optimization 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:06-Experimental-evaluation-the-service-coverage-problem"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

% First paragraph has no indentation.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The high-performance of PRATO, the radio-coverage simulation framework presented
 in Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:04-Framework-design-and-implementation"

\end_inset

, allows dealing with big problem instances in a reduced amount of time.
 Additionally, it enables tackling optimization problems that, because of
 their size, are out-of-reach of traditional approaches, mainly due to the
 computational-time complexity of their objective-function evaluation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter, the challenge is to exploit PRATO for solving one the of
 classic optimization problems of radio networks: the service-coverage problem.
 Considering the minimization of the total amount of pilot power subject
 to a full coverage constraint, a novel optimization approach is introduced.
 The presented method, based on parallel autonomous agents, gives very good
 solutions to the problem in an acceptable amount of time.
 The parallel implementation takes full advantage of GPU hardware in order
 to achieve considerable speed-up.
 The analysis of the experimental results, considering six real-world, radio
 networks of different sizes, studies solution-quality and performance aspects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The content of this chapter extends the research work published by the author
 in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Benedicic_Pilot.power.optimization:2010"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Benedicic-A_GPU_based_parallel_agent_optimization_approach:2013"

\end_inset

.
 The rest of this chapter is organized as follows.
 Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:06-Motivation"

\end_inset

 gives a description of the coverage problem and its motivation from the
 mobile operator's perspective.
 In Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:06-Related-work"

\end_inset

, a short overview of related research works is given, before formally introduci
ng the key elements of the service-coverage problem in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:06-Radio_network_model"

\end_inset

.
 The parallel-agent approach, as well as the strategies used for result
 comparison, are presented in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:06-Optimization-approaches"

\end_inset

, followed by the simulations and their analyses in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:06-Simulations"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Motivation 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:06-Motivation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving the service-coverage problem for radio networks has received a great
 deal of attention in the past years.
 Its complexity demands the confluence of different skills in areas such
 as propagation of radio signals, telecommunications and information systems,
 among others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even several decades after the launch of the first commercial GSM network,
 service-coverage planning remains a key problem that all mobile operators
 have to deal with.
 Its intricacy arises from the wide range of different combinations of configura
tion parameters and their evaluation-time complexity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regardless of the mobile technology used, e.g., GSM, UMTS or LTE, a lower
 transmit power generates less interference, which, in turn, translates
 into more capacity of the radio link (see Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:02-Principles_of_mobile_radio_networks"

\end_inset

).
 Additionally, reducing the transmit-power usage is also related to issues
 regarding human exposure to the electromagnetic fields generated by BS
 antennas
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Esposito_Genetic.optimization.for.optimum.3G.network.planning:2010"

\end_inset

.
 During the past few years, public opinion has been extremely sensitive
 regarding this issue, and thus many countries have already imposed safety
 standards to limit the electromagnetic field levels produced by antennas
 in a given range.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the UMTS perspective, minimizing pilot-power usage leaves more power
 available for increased network capacity.
 This is especially important if the traffic and other channels are configured
 relative to the pilot channel
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Holma_WCDMA.for.UMTS:2005"

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, as the demand for internet access and data services increases
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cunningham_Network.growth.theory.and.evidence:2010"

\end_inset

, so does the pressure on existing network infrastructure, making parameter
 optimization the only viable solution in the short-term
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nawrocki_Understanding:2006"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea of using autonomous agents for optimization is not new.
 It has proven to be a solid optimization approach for solving different
 types of problems, not only within the area of radio networks
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cheung_Realtime.video.using.agent.over.3G.networks:2005,Esposito_Genetic.optimization.for.optimum.3G.network.planning:2010"

\end_inset

, but also in other fields
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Valcarce_Applying.FDTD.to.the.coverage.prediction.of.WiMAX:2009,Vasile_Hybrid.multiagent.approach.for.optimization:2009"

\end_inset

.
 The increased computational-time complexity, when dealing with big problem
 instances, is tackled using a parallel, agent-based algorithm on GPU.
 This minimizes the overhead when deploying a larger number of agents working
 in parallel over the service area, only limited by the amount of memory
 available on the GPU.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Related work 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:06-Related-work"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several approaches in the literature that address the service-coverage
 problem in radio networks
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Amaldi-Radio_planning_and_coverage_optimization_of_3G_networks:2008,Nawrocki_Understanding:2006,Siomina_Pilot.power.optimization:2004"

\end_inset

.
 Some of them even claim to achieve near-optimal solutions
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Siomina:Minimum.pilot.power.for.service.coverage"

\end_inset

.
 As a matter of fact, most formulations are only useful for small network
 instances and often fail when challenged with larger, real-world networks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A genetic-algorithm approach for solving the service-coverage problem for
 GSM networks was presented in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lieska-Radion_coverage_optimization_with_genetic_algorithms:1998"

\end_inset

.
 The proposed solution is based on the physical distribution of BSs in order
 to maximize coverage.
 The simulations were performed on a test network with 40 candidate sites
 for BS antennas.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Siomina:Minimum.pilot.power.for.service.coverage"

\end_inset

, Siomina and Yuan considered the problem of minimizing the total amount
 of pilot power for UMTS networks, subject to a full coverage constraint.
 They tackled the problem with an iterative linear-programming approach,
 reporting very good results for some test networks, containing from 15
 to 65 base stations.
 The authors noted that bigger problem instances could not be solved because
 of hardware constraints on the target platform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As for LTE networks, the service-coverage problem was addressed in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Thampi-A_sparse_sampling_algorithm_for_self_optimisation_of_coverage_in_LTE_networks:2012"

\end_inset

.
 The authors presented an algorithm, based on reinforcement learning, to
 tackle three aspects of the coverage problem, i.e., coverage holes, weak
 coverage and pilot pollution.
 The experimental simulations, performed on 3 BSs, used different antenna-tilt
 configurations as the proposed solutions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The service-coverage problem, as presented in this chapter, corresponds
 to achieving full coverage of the target area, without coverage holes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Radio-network model 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:06-Radio_network_model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Extending the representation of a radio-network model from
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nawrocki2006understanding"

\end_inset

, this section presents the definitions of all the elements included in
 the mathematical model used for the simulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal here is to analyze the state of the network in a given situation,
 i.e., a ‘snapshot’ at an arbitrary instance.
 Radio-network planning tools, including the commercial ones, typically
 rely on static analysis
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Niemela-Performance_of_static_WCDMA_simulator:2005"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A snapshot consists of a set of UEs having individual properties, such as
 location, and equipment type, that provides an estimate of the average
 network behavior.
 The static approach inherently ignores dynamic effects that influence the
 system, like fast power control, but the analysis relies on having multiple
 independent snapshots to produce an average behavior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another alternative is to consider using a dynamic tool for radio-network
 planning
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hamalainen-Advanced_WCDMA_radio_network_simulator:1999,Hoppe-Fast_planning_of_efficient_WCDMA_radio_networks:2001"

\end_inset

.
 A dynamic simulation considers all Radio-Resource Management
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(RRM
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
prefix "A"
symbol "RRM"
description "Radio-resource management."

\end_inset

) functionality, as well as user mobility.
 However, when compared to the static approach, a major disadvantage of
 the dynamic simulation is the large computational time it requires.
 This clearly excludes the possibility of achieving fast performance evaluations
 of a network, which is one of the objectives of this thesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering that the performance of a static approach was demonstrated to
 provide sufficiently accurate results compared to a fully dynamic approach
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RadioNetworkPlanningAndOptimisationForUMTS,Laiho-Verification_of_WCDMA_network_planning_prediction_with_dynamic_simulations:2001"

\end_inset

, the former one is implemented in the remaining of this work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For additional information regarding mathematical models for radio networks
 and signal propagations, see
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RadioNetworkPlanningAndOptimisationForUMTS,Nawrocki_Understanding:2006,Stuber-Principles_of_mobile_communication:2011"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Basic elements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a radio network with a set of antenna installations (cells), 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
prefix "S"
symbol "$C$"
description "Set of antenna installations (cells) in a mobile network."

\end_inset

.
 A RSG of a given resolution represents a geographical area, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathrm{total}}$
\end_inset

, within which a set of UEs, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
prefix "S"
symbol "$M$"
description "Set of mobile devices or users of a mobile network."

\end_inset

, is spatially distributed over the pixels of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathrm{total}}$
\end_inset

.
 Further, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{cm}^{\downarrow}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
prefix "S"
symbol "$l_{cm}^{\\downarrow}$"
description "Downlink attenuation factor between cell $c\\in C$ and mobile $m\\in M$."

\end_inset

 is defined as the downlink attenuation factor between cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in C$
\end_inset

 and UE 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{mc}^{\uparrow}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
prefix "S"
symbol "$l_{mc}^{\\uparrow}$"
description "Uplink attenuation factor between mobile $m\\in M$ and cell $c\\in C$."

\end_inset

 represents the uplink attenuation factor between UE 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 The attenuation factor values are calculated by performing signal-propagation
 predictions for every pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(c,m)$
\end_inset

, using the radio-propagation model introduced in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:04-Radio_propagation_model"

\end_inset

.
 These predictions already include losses and gains from cabling, hardware,
 and user equipment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The amount of power allocated to the pilot signal of cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{c}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
prefix "S"
symbol "$p_{c}$"
description "Pilot-power setting of cell $c\\in C$."

\end_inset

, and it can adopt any value from the sorted set of available pilot power
 levels, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{c}=\{p_{c}^{1},p_{c}^{2},...,p_{c}^{k}\}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
prefix "S"
symbol "$P_{c}$"
description "Set of candidate CPICH power settings for cell $c\\in C$."

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{c}^{k}$
\end_inset

 is the maximum power.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on the introduced elements, the received pilot power from cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 to UE 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{cm}^{\downarrow}p_{c}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Coverage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An UE 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 within the area 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathrm{covered}}$
\end_inset

 is under service coverage if at least one cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 covers it.
 Cell coverage is provided to an UE 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 from a cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 if its signal-to-interference ratio, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{SINR}(c,m)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
prefix "S"
symbol "$\\mathrm{SINR}(c,m)$"
description "Signal-to-interference ratio (SIR) from cell $c\\in C$ to mobile $m\\in M$."

\end_inset

, at the RSG pixel where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is located, is not lower than a given threshold, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\mathrm{cov}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
prefix "S"
symbol "$\\gamma^{\\mathrm{cov}}$"
description "Signal-to-interference ratio (SIR) coverage threshold."

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{SINR}(c,m)=\frac{l_{cm}^{\downarrow}p_{c}}{\mathrm{N}_{0}+\sum_{i\in C}l_{im}^{\downarrow}p_{i}}\ge\gamma^{\mathrm{cov}},\label{eq:06-Signal_to_interference_ratio}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}_{0}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
prefix "S"
symbol "$\\mathrm{N}_0$"
description "Thermal noise."

\end_inset

 is the thermal noise
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RadioNetworkPlanningAndOptimisationForUMTS"

\end_inset

.
 For convenience, a binary function is defined to determine the coverage
 of a UE 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 by a cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 So, for any pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(c,m)$
\end_inset

, the coverage of UE 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 by cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is defined as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{cov}(c,m)=\begin{cases}
1 & if\,\mathrm{SINR}(c,m)\ge\gamma^{\mathrm{cov}}\\
0 & otherwise
\end{cases}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
prefix "S"
symbol "$\\mathrm{cov}(c,m)$"
description "Binary function to assert the coverage of a  mobile $m\\in M$ by from a cell $c\\in C$."

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
A set, denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{m}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
prefix "S"
symbol "$C_{m}$"
description "Subset of cells, $C_m\\subset C$, that cover a mobile $m\\in M$."

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{m}\subset C$
\end_inset

, contains all the cells covering an UE 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 From this set, the cell with the highest 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{SINR}(c,m)$
\end_inset

 is refered to as the best server, and denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{m}^{*}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
prefix "S"
symbol "$c_{m}^*$"
description "Best-serving cell of mobile $m\\in M$."

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Notice that the described radio-network model is easily adaptable for different
 mobile technologies, e.g., GSM, UMTS and LTE.
 For example, if solving the service-coverage problem for UMTS, it would
 be reasonable to assume that all cells in the network operate at maximum
 power, and adapt Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:06-Signal_to_interference_ratio"

\end_inset

) accordingly.
 This is, from the interference point of view, the worst-case scenario
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chen-Yuan_CPICH.optimization:2008,Siomina:Minimum.pilot.power.for.service.coverage"

\end_inset

.
 This assumption guarantees, that even under heavy user traffic, full coverage
 of the service area is maintained, due to the cell-breathing principle
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Holma_WCDMA.for.UMTS:2005"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Problem definition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the problem of optimization of pilot powers for service coverage, the
 objective is to find a set of pilot-power settings for all cells in the
 network, such that the total pilot power used is minimized, and a given
 service coverage criteria is fulfilled.
 In other words, solving the service-coverage problem corresponds to finding
 the pilot power levels 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{c}$
\end_inset

, for all cells 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in C$
\end_inset

, such that coverage of at least 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 UEs is guaranteed, while the total amount of pilot power used is minimized.
 Here, full coverage of the service area is being considered, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\vert M\vert$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, the optimization objective is defined as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P^{*}=\min\sum_{c\in C}p_{c},\, p_{c}\in P_{c}\label{eq:06-Objective_function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
subject to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\sum_{m\in M}\mathrm{cov}(c_{m}^{*},m)}{b}=1.\label{eq:06-Coverage_constraint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It has been proved that the problem of pilot-power optimization for full
 coverage of the service area is 
\begin_inset Formula $NP$
\end_inset

-hard, since it can be reduced to the set-covering problem
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Varbrand_Mathematical.programming.approach:2003"

\end_inset

.
 Consequently, as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $P\neq NP$
\end_inset

, it is unfeasible that a polynomial-time algorithm exists, which is able
 to find an exact solution to this problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Optimization approaches 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:06-Optimization-approaches"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since some of the analyzed problem instances are part of a real mobile network
 deployed in Slovenia by Telekom Slovenije, d.d., there are no references
 in the literature of other optimization techniques dealing with exactly
 the same data set.
 For this reason, two different strategies for setting the pilot power are
 being presented.
 They should provide a basis for the comparison of the experimental results.
 The first strategy is the attenuation-based pilot power, presented in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Siomina_Pilot.power.optimization:2004"

\end_inset

, in which a pixel of the service area is always covered by the cell with
 the maximum attenuation-factor value, i.e., the minimum path loss.
 The second strategy is the presented parallel-agent approach, based on
 ideas inspired by two-dimensional cellular automata
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Sarkar_Cellular.automata.history:2000"

\end_inset

 and metaheuristics
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Talbi_Metaheuristics:2009"

\end_inset

.
 A detailed description is given in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:06-Parallel_agent_approach"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar criteria for result comparison have also been used in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Siomina_Pilot.power.optimization:2004,Siomina:Minimum.pilot.power.for.service.coverage"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Attenuation-based approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first heuristic for setting the pilot power of all cells in the network
 is known as attenuation-based, since it relies on the downlink-attenuation
 factor, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{cm}^{\downarrow}$
\end_inset

.
 An UE located on some pixel of the service area is always covered by the
 cell with the minimum path loss, i.e., the highest 
\begin_inset Formula $l{}_{cm}^{\downarrow}$
\end_inset

 value.
 Whenever the maximum available power, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{c}^{k}$
\end_inset

, is the same for all the cells in the network, this is equivalent to selecting
 the cell with the minimum required pilot power to cover a UE 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, under this assumption, the cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 covering UE 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is identified as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{cm}^{\mathrm{att}}=\min p_{c}\,\forall c\in C\iff\mathrm{cov}(c,m)=1\label{eq:06-Attenuation_based-power}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Picking the cells conforming to Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:06-Attenuation_based-power"

\end_inset

) and setting the pilot powers accordingly, full coverage of the service
 area is achieved.
 The solution exhibits a total pilot power defined as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P^{\mathrm{att}}=\sum_{c\in C}\max p_{cm}^{\mathrm{att}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The procedure to find a cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 for every UE 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 in the service area consists in sorting, in descending order, all UEs by
 their attenuation-factor values, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{cm}^{\downarrow}$
\end_inset

.
 The solution is thus established by the first 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 UEs of the sorted sequence, taking the maximum pilot-power setting for
 a cell into account, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{cm}^{\mathrm{att}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Parallel-agent approach 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:06-Parallel_agent_approach"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the parallel-agent approach, a set of autonomous worker agents explore
 the target geographical area, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathrm{total}}$
\end_inset

, in order to optimize the pilot-power consumption.
 Each agent randomly moves over the 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathrm{total}}$
\end_inset

 as it dictates different changes to the pilot power of the cells.
 PRATO, the radio-coverage framework presented in Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:04-Framework-design-and-implementation"

\end_inset

, performs the objective-function evaluations and radio-propagation predictions
 based on the proposed changes of the agents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The moving process during the optimization is strictly random.
 However, several physical properties that are exclusive to the service-coverage
 problem are being exploited during the exploration of the search space.
 Additionally, whenever the current solution breaks any of the given constraints
, the optimization process is guided back to the space of valid solutions,
 providing a mechanism for improving exploration and escaping from local
 optima.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because the behaviour of the agents is independent between each other, a
 parallel implementation is fairly straight-forward to achieve.
 Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:06-Architecture_of_the_system_on_GPU"

\end_inset

 shows the architecture of the agent-optimization system.
 In this GPU-only architecture, agents work in a parallel and autonomous
 manner, while the evaluator reacts to their changes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename img/architecture.eps
	lyxscale 50
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Architecture of the parallel, agent-based optimization system on GPU.
\emph on

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:06-Architecture_of_the_system_on_GPU"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Objective-function evaluation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The evaluator represents a central component of the optimization system.
 It reacts to the pilot-power changes by recalculating the objective-function
 value.
 Recall that the objective-function evaluation involves the radio-coverage
 prediction of the service area and the calculation of the total pilot power
 used by the cells in the target network.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After a short initialization, during which the attenuation-factor matrices
 of all the cells and the interference matrix are calculated, the evaluator
 computes the coverage of the service area based on the pilot powers supplied
 as the initial solution.
 Initial solutions are randomly generated from valid pilot-power settings
 that conform to the full coverage constraint.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The evaluator also maintains a special part of the memory (see 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Coordinates of uncovered cells
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:06-Architecture_of_the_system_on_GPU"

\end_inset

) that is intended for registering uncovered areas, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A_{\mathrm{covered}}}$
\end_inset

.
 If Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:06-Coverage_constraint"

\end_inset

) does not hold, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

special
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 agents randomly select a location from this portion of memory so that a
 valid solution may be reached again.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is worth mentioning that the evaluator itself has no influence in the
 optimization process from a quality point-of-view.
 Its task is to provide feedback and updated information to the agents that
 move through the service area.
 From a performance point-of-view, the importance of the evaluator is significan
t, as it will be shown in the following sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The evaluation of the objective function was completely implemented on the
 GPU using OpenCL (see Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:02-OpenCL"

\end_inset

).
 The reason behind this decision is the impact objective-function evaluation
 has on the performance of the optimization system as a whole, as discussed
 in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:02-Black_box_optimization"

\end_inset

.
 The implementation of the agents is also based on the GPU, which drastically
 reduces the number of data transfers between CPU and GPU, since all problem
 elements are available on the GPU during the optimization process.
 Consequently, careful memory utilization and organization are critical
 to successfully accommodate all involved problem elements on the GPU, the
 memory of which is significantly smaller than the RAM available in desktop
 computers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Autonomous agents
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The agents apply the pilot-power changes only considering local information.
 Each of them encapsulates a set of steps that is consistently applied as
 it randomly moves through the service area of the network.
 Whenever an agent arrives at a new location, the set of covering cells
 is calculated, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The step set an agent applies following this point is directly related to
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert C_{m}\vert$
\end_inset

, whereas its movement is determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert\overline{A_{\mathrm{covered}}}\vert$
\end_inset

, i.e., the area without service coverage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The behavior of an agent is dictated by the pseudo-code shown in Algorithm
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:07-Agent-behavior"

\end_inset

.
 The first four steps are responsible for guiding its movements.
 The coordinates are randomly selected from two sets, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathrm{total}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A_{\mathrm{covered}}}$
\end_inset

.
 Only 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

special
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 agents may move to a location without service coverage, and they apply
 the step set 
\begin_inset Formula $SS_{0}$
\end_inset

 for as long as the solution is not valid.
 The portion of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

special
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 agents used for correcting a solution is a parameter of the optimization
 process.
 During the following steps of Algorithm
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:07-Agent-behavior"

\end_inset

, the agent applies step sets 
\begin_inset Formula $SS_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $SS_{1}$
\end_inset

 based on the number of cells in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float algorithm
